# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: exhaust-gas-recirculation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] In the study of combustion, the **adiabatic flame temperature** is the temperature reached by a flame under ideal conditions.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] It is an upper bound of the temperature that is reached in actual processes.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] There are two types of adiabatic flame temperature: *constant volume* and *constant pressure*, depending on how the process is completed.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] The constant volume adiabatic flame temperature is the temperature that results from a complete combustion process that occurs without any work, heat transfer or changes in kinetic or potential energy.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Its temperature is higher than in the *constant pressure* process because no energy is utilized to change the volume of the system (i.e., generate work).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] In daily life, the vast majority of flames one encounters are those caused by rapid oxidation of hydrocarbons in materials such as wood, wax, fat, plastics, propane, and gasoline.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] The constant-pressure adiabatic flame temperature of such substances in air is in a relatively narrow range around 1,950 °C (2,220 K; 3,540 °F).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] This is mostly because the heat of combustion of these compounds is roughly proportional to the amount of oxygen consumed, which proportionally increases the amount of air that has to be heated, so the effect of a larger heat of combustion on the flame temperature is offset.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Incomplete reaction at higher temperature further curtails the effect of a larger heat of combustion.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Because most combustion processes that happen naturally occur in the open air, there is nothing that confines the gas to a particular volume like the cylinder in an engine.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] As a result, these substances will burn at a constant pressure, which allows the gas to expand during the process.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Assuming initial atmospheric conditions (1 bar and 20 °C), the following table lists the flame temperature for various fuels under constant pressure conditions.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] The temperatures mentioned here are for a stoichiometric fuel-oxidizer mixture (i.e. equivalence ratio *φ* = 1).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] These are theoretical, not actual, flame temperatures produced by a flame that loses no heat.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] The closest will be the hottest part of a flame, where the combustion reaction is most efficient.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] This also assumes complete combustion (e.g. perfectly balanced, non-smoky, usually bluish flame).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Several values in the table significantly disagree with the literature or predictions by online calculators.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] where, ${}_{R}Q_{P}$ and ${}_{R}W_{P}$ are the heat and work transferred from the system to the surroundings during the process, respectively, and $U_{R}$ and $U_{P}$ are the internal energy of the reactants and products, respectively.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] There is also no heat transfer because the process is defined to be adiabatic: ${}_{R}Q_{P}=0$ .
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] As a result, the internal energy of the products is equal to the internal energy of the reactants: $U_{P}=U_{R}$ .
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Again there is no heat transfer occurring because the process is defined to be adiabatic: ${}_{R}Q_{P}=0$ .
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Recalling the definition of enthalpy we obtain $H_{P}=H_{R}$ .
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] We see that the adiabatic flame temperature of the constant pressure process is lower than that of the constant volume process.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] This is because some of the energy released during combustion goes, as work, into changing the volume of the control system.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] If we make the assumption that combustion goes to completion (i.e. forming only CO 2 and H 2O), we can calculate the adiabatic flame temperature by hand either at stoichiometric conditions or lean of stoichiometry (excess air).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] and use the equilibrium constant for this reaction, we will have enough variables to complete the calculation.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Different fuels with different levels of energy and molar constituents will have different adiabatic flame temperatures.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] We can see by the following figure why nitromethane (CH3NO2) is often used as a power boost for cars.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Since each molecule of nitromethane contains an oxidant with relatively high-energy bonds between nitrogen and oxygen, it can burn much hotter than hydrocarbons or oxygen-containing methanol.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] This is analogous to adding pure oxygen, which also raises the adiabatic flame temperature.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] This in turn allows it to build up more pressure during a constant volume process.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] The higher the pressure, the more force upon the piston creating more work and more power in the engine.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] It stays relatively hot rich of stoichiometry because it contains its own oxidant.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] However, continual running of an engine on nitromethane will eventually melt the piston and/or cylinder because of this higher temperature.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] In real world applications, complete combustion does not typically occur.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Chemistry dictates that dissociation and kinetics will change the composition of the products.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] There are a number of programs available that can calculate the adiabatic flame temperature taking into account dissociation through equilibrium constants (Stanjan, NASA CEA, AFTP).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] The following figure illustrates that the effects of dissociation tend to lower the adiabatic flame temperature.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/adiabatic-flame-temperature] This result can be explained through Le Chatelier's principle.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] In an internal combustion engine or industrial furnace, the air–fuel ratio is an important measure for anti-pollution and performance-tuning reasons.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] If exactly enough air is provided to completely burn all of the fuel (**stoichiometric combustion**), the ratio is known as the **stoichiometric mixture**, often abbreviated to **stoich**.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] Ratios lower than stoichiometric (where the fuel is in excess) are considered "rich".
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] Rich mixtures are less efficient, but may produce more power and burn cooler.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] Ratios higher than stoichiometric (where the air is in excess) are considered "lean".
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] Lean mixtures are more efficient but may cause higher temperatures, which can lead to the formation of nitrogen oxides.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] Some engines are designed with features to allow lean-burn.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] For precise air–fuel ratio calculations, the oxygen content of combustion air should be specified because of different air density due to different altitude or intake air temperature, possible dilution by ambient water vapor, or enrichment by oxygen additions.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] An **air-fuel ratio meter** monitors the air–fuel ratio of an internal combustion engine.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] Also called **air–fuel ratio gauge**, **air–fuel meter**, or **air–fuel gauge**, it reads the voltage output of an oxygen sensor, sometimes also called **AFR sensor** or lambda sensor.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] The original narrow-band oxygen sensors became factory installed standard in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] In recent years a newer and much more accurate wide-band sensor, though more expensive, has become available.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] Most stand-alone narrow-band meters have 10 LEDs and some have more.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] Also common, narrow band meters in round housings with the standard mounting 52 and 67 mm (2+1⁄16 and 2+5⁄8 in) diameters, as other types of car 'gauges'.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] Analogue 'needle' style gauges are also available.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] In theory, a stoichiometric mixture has just enough air to completely burn the available fuel.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] In practice, this is never quite achieved, due primarily to the very short time available in an internal combustion engine for each combustion cycle.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] Most of the combustion process is completed in approximately 2 milliseconds at an engine speed of 6,000 revolutions per minute (100 revolutions per second, or 10 milliseconds per revolution of the crankshaft.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] For a four-stroke engine this would mean 5 milliseconds for each piston stroke, and 20 milliseconds to complete one 720 degree Otto cycle).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] This is the time that elapses from the spark plug firing until 90% of the fuel–air mix is combusted, typically some 80 degrees of crankshaft rotation later.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] Catalytic converters are designed to work best when the exhaust gases passing through them are the result of nearly perfect combustion.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] A perfectly stoichiometric mixture burns very hot and can damage engine components if the engine is placed under high load at this fuel–air mixture.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] Due to the high flame temperatures at this mixture, detonation is possible under high load.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] (Detonation is known as knocking or pinging).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] Such detonation can cause serious engine damage as the uncontrolled burning of the fuel-air mix can create very high pressures in the cylinder.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] As a consequence, stoichiometric mixtures are only used under light to low-moderate load conditions.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] For acceleration and high-load conditions, a richer mixture (lower air–fuel ratio) is used to produce cooler combustion products and so avoid overheating of the cylinder head, and thus prevent detonation.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] The stoichiometric mixture for a gasoline engine is the ideal ratio of air to fuel that burns all fuel with no excess air.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] For gasoline fuel, the stoichiometric air–fuel mixture is about 14.7:1 i.e. for every one gram of fuel, 14.7 grams of air are required.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] Any mixture greater than 14.7:1 is considered a lean mixture; any less than 14.7:1 is a rich mixture – given perfect (ideal) "test" fuel (gasoline consisting of solely *n*-heptane and iso-octane).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] In reality, most fuels consist of a combination of heptane, octane, a handful of other alkanes, plus additives including detergents, and possibly oxygenators such as MTBE (methyl *tert*-butyl ether) or ethanol/methanol.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] These compounds all alter the stoichiometric ratio, with most of the additives pushing the ratio downward (oxygenators bring extra oxygen to the combustion event in liquid form that is released at the time of combustions; for MTBE-laden fuel, a stoichiometric ratio can be as low as 14.1:1).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] Vehicles that use an oxygen sensor or other feedback loops to control fuel to air ratio (lambda control), compensate automatically for this change in the fuel's stoichiometric rate by measuring the exhaust gas composition and controlling fuel volume.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] Vehicles that use oxygen sensors can monitor the air–fuel ratio with an air–fuel ratio meter.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] In the typical air to natural gas combustion burner, a double-cross limit strategy is employed to ensure ratio control.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] The strategy involves adding the opposite flow feedback into the limiting control of the respective gas (air or fuel).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] This assures ratio control within an acceptable margin.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] There are other terms commonly used when discussing the mixture of air and fuel in internal combustion engines.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] Air-fuel ratio is the ratio between the *mass* of air and the mass of fuel in the air-fuel mix at any given moment.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] The mass is the mass of all constituents that compose the air or fuel, whether they take part in the combustion or not.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] For pure octane the stoichiometric mixture is approximately 15.1:1, or *λ* of 1.00 exactly.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] In naturally aspirated engines powered by octane, maximum power is frequently reached at AFRs ranging from 12.5 to 13.3:1 or *λ* of 0.850 to 0.901.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] The air-fuel ratio of 12:1 is considered as the maximum output ratio, whereas the air-fuel ratio of 16:1 is considered as the maximum fuel economy ratio.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] Air–fuel equivalence ratio, *λ* (lambda), is the ratio of actual AFR to stoichiometry for a given mixture.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] *λ* = 1.0 is at stoichiometry, rich mixtures *λ* < 1.0, and lean mixtures *λ* > 1.0.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] There is a direct relationship between *λ* and AFR.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] To calculate AFR from a given *λ*, multiply the measured *λ* by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] Alternatively, to recover *λ* from an AFR, divide AFR by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] Because the composition of common fuels varies seasonally, and because many modern vehicles can handle different fuels when tuning, it makes more sense to talk about *λ* values rather than AFR.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] Most practical AFR devices actually measure the amount of residual oxygen (for lean mixes) or unburnt hydrocarbons (for rich mixtures) in the exhaust gas.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] The **fuel–air equivalence ratio**, *Φ* (phi), of a system is defined as the ratio of the fuel-to-oxidizer ratio to the stoichiometric fuel-to-oxidizer ratio.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] where *m* represents the mass, *n* represents a number of moles, subscript st stands for stoichiometric conditions.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] The advantage of using equivalence ratio over fuel–oxidizer ratio is that it takes into account (and is therefore independent of) both mass and molar values for the fuel and the oxidizer.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] Consider, for example, a mixture of one mole of ethane (C 2H 6) and one mole of oxygen (O 2).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] To compare it with the equivalence ratio, we need to determine the fuel–oxidizer ratio of ethane and oxygen mixture.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] This is not the case if one uses fuel–oxidizer ratio, which takes different values for different mixtures.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] In industrial fired heaters, power plant steam generators, and large gas-fired turbines, the more common terms are percent excess combustion air and percent stoichiometric air.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] For example, excess combustion air of 15 percent means that 15 percent more than the required stoichiometric air (or 115 percent of stoichiometric air) is being used.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] A combustion control point can be defined by specifying the percent excess air (or oxygen) in the oxidant, or by specifying the percent oxygen in the combustion product.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/air-fuel-ratio] An air–fuel ratio meter may be used to measure the percent oxygen in the combustion gas, from which the percent excess oxygen can be calculated from stoichiometry and a mass balance for fuel combustion.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/backpressure] In distributed systems in particular event-driven architecture, back pressure is a technique to regulate flow of data, ensuring that components do not become overwhelmed.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/backpressure] In a piston-ported two-stroke engine, however, the situation is more complicated, due to the need to prevent unburned fuel/air mixture from passing right through the cylinders into the exhaust.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/backpressure] During the exhaust phase of the cycle, backpressure is even more undesirable than in a four-stroke engine, as there is less time available for exhaust and the lack of pumping action from the piston to force the exhaust out of the cylinder.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/backpressure] However, since the exhaust port necessarily remains open for a time after scavenging is completed, unburned mixture can follow the exhaust out of the cylinder, wasting fuel and increasing pollution.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/backpressure] This can only be prevented if the pressure at the exhaust port is greater than that in the cylinder.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/backpressure] Since the timing of this process is determined mainly by exhaust system geometry, which is extremely difficult to make variable, correct timing and therefore optimum engine efficiency can typically only be achieved over a small part of the engine's range of operating speed.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/backpressure] Back-pressure is a useful diagnostic feature of problems with the chromatography column.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/backpressure] Rapid chromatography is favoured by columns packed with very small particles, which create high back-pressures.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/backpressure] Column designers use "kinetic plots" to show the performance of a column at a constant back-pressure, usually selected as the maximum that a system's pump can reliably produce.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] An **orifice plate** is a device used for measuring flow rate, reducing pressure or restricting flow (in the latter two cases it is often called a **restriction plate**).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] An orifice plate is a thin plate with a hole in it, which is usually placed in a pipe.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] When a fluid (whether liquid or gaseous) passes through the orifice, its pressure builds up slightly upstream of the orifice but as the fluid is forced to converge to pass through the hole, the velocity increases and the fluid pressure decreases.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] A little downstream of the orifice the flow reaches its point of maximum convergence, the *vena contracta* (see drawing to the right) where the velocity reaches its maximum and the pressure reaches its minimum.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] Beyond that, the flow expands, the velocity falls and the pressure increases.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] By measuring the difference in fluid pressure across tappings upstream and downstream of the plate, the flow rate can be obtained from Bernoulli's equation using coefficients established from extensive research.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] The overall pressure loss in the pipe due to an orifice plate is lower than the measured differential pressure, typically by a factor of $1-\beta ^{1.9}$ .
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] Under these circumstances and when the orifice plate is constructed and installed according to appropriate standards, the flow rate can easily be determined using published formulae based on substantial research and published in industry, national and international standards.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] An orifice plate is called a **calibrated orifice** if it has been calibrated with an appropriate fluid flow and a traceable flow measurement device.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] Plates are commonly made with sharp-edged circular orifices and installed concentric with the pipe and with pressure tappings at one of three standard pairs of distances upstream and downstream of the plate; these types are covered by ISO 5167 and other major standards.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] The edges may be rounded or conical, the plate may have an orifice the same size as the pipe except for a segment at top or bottom which is obstructed, the orifice may be installed eccentric to the pipe, and the pressure tappings may be at other positions.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] Variations on these possibilities are covered in various standards and handbooks.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] Each combination gives rise to different coefficients of discharge which can be predicted so long as various conditions are met, conditions which differ from one type to another.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] Once the orifice plate is designed and installed, the flow rate can often be indicated with an acceptably low uncertainty simply by taking the square root of the differential pressure across the orifice's pressure tappings and applying an appropriate constant.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] Orifice plates are also used to reduce pressure or restrict flow, in which case they are often called restriction plates.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] These types are covered by ISO 5167 and other major standards.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] The measured differential pressure differs for each combination and so the coefficient of discharge used in flow calculations depends partly on the tapping positions.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] The simplest installations use single tappings upstream and downstream, but in some circumstances these may be unreliable; they might be blocked by solids or gas-bubbles, or the flow profile might be uneven so that the pressures at the tappings are higher or lower than the average in those planes.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] In these situations multiple tappings can be used, arranged circumferentially around the pipe and joined by a piezometer ring, or (in the case of corner taps) annular slots running completely round the internal circumference of the orifice carrier.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] Standards and handbooks are mainly concerned with **sharp-edged thin** plates.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] In these, the leading edge is sharp and free of burrs and the cylindrical section of the orifice is short, either because the entire plate is thin or because the downstream edge of the plate is bevelled.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] Exceptions include the **quarter-circle** or **quadrant-edge** orifice, which has a fully rounded leading edge and no cylindrical section, and the **conical inlet** or **conical entrance** plate which has a bevelled leading edge and a very short cylindrical section.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] The orifices are normally concentric with the pipe (the **eccentric** orifice is a specific exception) and circular (except in the specific case of the **segmental** or **chord** orifice, in which the plate obstructs just a segment of the pipe).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] Standards and handbooks stipulate that the upstream surface of the plate is particularly flat and smooth.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] Standards and handbooks stipulate a well-developed flow profile; velocities will be lower at the pipe wall than in the centre but not eccentric or jetting.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] Similarly the flow downstream of the plate must be unobstructed, otherwise the downstream pressure will be affected.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] To achieve this, the pipe must be acceptably circular, smooth and straight for stipulated distances.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] Sometimes when it is impossible to provide enough straight pipe, flow conditioners such as tube bundles or plates with multiple holes are inserted into the pipe to straighten and develop the flow profile, but even these require a further length of straight pipe before the orifice itself.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] Some standards and handbooks also provide for flows from or into large spaces rather than pipes, stipulating that the region before or after the plate is free of obstruction and abnormalities in the flow.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] The above expression for $q_{v}^{'}$ gives the theoretical volume flow rate.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] Deriving the above equations used the cross-section of the orifice opening and is not as realistic as using the minimum cross-section at the vena contracta.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] In addition, frictional losses may not be negligible and viscosity and turbulence effects may be present.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] For that reason, the coefficient of discharge $C_{d}$ is introduced.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] Methods exist for determining the coefficient of discharge as a function of the Reynolds number.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] The parameter ${\frac {1}{\sqrt {1-\beta ^{4}}}}$ is often referred to as the *velocity of approach factor* and multiplying the coefficient of discharge by that parameter (as was done above) produces the flow coefficient C .
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] Methods also exist for determining the flow coefficient as a function of the beta $\beta$ and the location of the downstream pressure sensing tap.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] For rough approximations, the flow coefficient may be assumed to be between 0.60 and 0.75.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] For a first approximation, a flow coefficient of 0.62 can be used as this approximates to fully developed flow.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] An orifice only works well when supplied with a fully developed flow profile.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] This is achieved by a long upstream length (20 to 40 pipe diameters, depending on Reynolds number) or the use of a flow conditioner.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] Orifice plates are small and inexpensive but do not recover the pressure drop as well as a venturi, nozzle, or venturi-nozzle does.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] Venturis also require much less straight pipe upstream.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] A venturi meter is more efficient, but usually more expensive and less accurate (unless calibrated in a laboratory) than an orifice plate.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] In general, equation (2) is applicable only for incompressible flows.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] It can be modified by introducing the expansibility factor, (also called the expansion factor) $\epsilon$ to account for the compressibility of gasses.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] $\epsilon$ is 1.0 for incompressible fluids and it can be calculated for compressible gases using empirically determined formulae as shown below in computation.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] For smaller values of β (such as restriction plates with β less than 0.25 and discharge from tanks), if the fluid is compressible, the rate of flow depends on whether the flow has become choked.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] Flow rates through an orifice plate can be calculated without specifically calibrating the individual flowmeter so long as the construction and installation of the device complies with the stipulations of the relevant standard or handbook.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] The calculation takes account of the fluid and fluid conditions, the pipe size, the orifice size and the measured differential pressure; it also takes account of the coefficient of discharge of the orifice plate, which depends upon the orifice type and the positions of the pressure tappings.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] With local pressure tappings (corner, flange and D+D/2), sharp-edged orifices have coefficients around 0.6 to 0.63, while the coefficients for conical entrance plates are in the range 0.73 to 0.734 and for quarter-circle plates 0.77 to 0.85.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] The coefficients of sharp-edged orifices vary more with fluids and flow rates than the coefficients of conical-entrance and quarter-circle plates, especially at low flows and high viscosities.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] For compressible flows such as flows of gases or steam, an *expansibility factor* or *expansion factor* is also calculated.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] This factor is primarily a function of the ratio of the measured differential pressure to the fluid pressure and so can vary significantly as the flow rate varies, especially at high differential pressures and low static pressures.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] The equations below largely follow the notation of the international standard ISO 5167 and use SI units.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/calibrated-orifice] The overall pressure loss caused by an orifice plate is less than the differential pressure measured across tappings near the plate.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] It is a trace gas in Earth's atmosphere at 428 parts per million (ppm), or about 0.043% (as of July 2025) having risen from pre-industrial levels of 280 ppm or about 0.028%.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Burning fossil fuels is the main cause of these increased CO2 concentrations, which are the primary cause of climate change.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Its concentration in Earth's pre-industrial atmosphere since late in the Precambrian was regulated by organisms and geological features.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Plants, algae and cyanobacteria use energy from sunlight to synthesize carbohydrates from carbon dioxide and water in a process called photosynthesis, which produces oxygen as a waste product.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] In turn, oxygen is consumed and CO2 is released as waste by all aerobic organisms when they metabolize organic compounds to produce energy by respiration.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is released from organic materials when they decay or combust, such as in forest fires.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] When carbon dioxide dissolves in water, it forms carbonate and mainly bicarbonate (HCO3–), which causes ocean acidification as atmospheric CO2 levels increase.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is 53% denser than dry air, but is long-lived and thoroughly mixes in the atmosphere.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] About half of excess CO2 emissions to the atmosphere are absorbed by land and ocean carbon sinks.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] These sinks can become saturated and are volatile, as decay and wildfires result in the CO2 being released back into the atmosphere.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] CO2, or the carbon it holds, is eventually sequestered (stored for the long term) in rocks and organic deposits like coal, petroleum and natural gas.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Nearly all CO2 produced by humans goes into the atmosphere.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Less than 1% of CO2 produced annually is put to commercial use, mostly in the fertilizer industry and in the oil and gas industry for enhanced oil recovery.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Other commercial applications include food and beverage production, metal fabrication, cooling, fire suppression and stimulating plant growth in greenhouses.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The symmetry of a carbon dioxide molecule is linear and centrosymmetric at its equilibrium geometry.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The length of the carbon–oxygen bond in carbon dioxide is 116.3 pm, noticeably shorter than the roughly 140 pm length of a typical single C–O bond, and shorter than most other C–O multiply bonded functional groups such as carbonyls.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Since it is centrosymmetric, the molecule has no electric dipole moment.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] As a linear triatomic molecule, CO2 has four vibrational modes as shown in the diagram.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] In the symmetric and the antisymmetric stretching modes, the atoms move along the axis of the molecule.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] There are two bending modes, which are degenerate, meaning that they have the same frequency and same energy, because of the symmetry of the molecule.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] When a molecule touches a surface or touches another molecule, the two bending modes can differ in frequency because the interaction is different for the two modes.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Some of the vibrational modes are observed in the infrared (IR) spectrum: the antisymmetric stretching mode at wavenumber 2349 cm−1 (wavelength 4.25 μm) and the degenerate pair of bending modes at 667 cm−1 (wavelength 15.0 μm).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The symmetric stretching mode does not create an electric dipole so is not observed in IR spectroscopy, but it is detected in Raman spectroscopy at 1388 cm−1 (wavelength 7.20 μm), with a Fermi resonance doublet at 1285 cm−1.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] In the gas phase, carbon dioxide molecules undergo significant vibrational motions and do not keep a fixed structure.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] However, in a Coulomb explosion imaging experiment, an instantaneous image of the molecular structure can be deduced.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Such an experiment has been performed for carbon dioxide.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The result of this experiment, and the conclusion of theoretical calculations based on an ab initio potential energy surface of the molecule, is that none of the molecules in the gas phase are ever exactly linear.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] This counter-intuitive result is trivially due to the fact that the nuclear motion volume element vanishes for linear geometries.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] This is so for all molecules except diatomic molecules.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is soluble in water, in which it reversibly forms H2CO3 (carbonic acid), which is a weak acid, because its ionization in water is incomplete.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Hence, the majority of the carbon dioxide is not converted into carbonic acid, but remains as CO2 molecules, not affecting the pH.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The relative concentrations of CO2, H2CO3, and the deprotonated forms HCO3– (bicarbonate) and CO32– (carbonate) depend on the pH.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] As shown in a Bjerrum plot, in neutral or slightly alkaline water (pH > 6.5), the bicarbonate form predominates (>50%) becoming the most prevalent (>95%) at the pH of seawater.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] In very alkaline water (pH > 10.4), the predominant (>50%) form is carbonate.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The oceans, being mildly alkaline with typical pH = 8.2–8.5, contain about 120 mg of bicarbonate per liter.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] where the denominator includes only covalently bound H2CO3 and does not include hydrated CO2(aq).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Since most of the dissolved CO2 remains as CO2 molecules, *K*a1(apparent) has a much larger denominator and a much smaller value than the true *K*a1.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The bicarbonate ion is an amphoteric species that can act as an acid or as a base, depending on pH of the solution.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] In organisms, carbonic acid production is catalysed by the enzyme known as carbonic anhydrase.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] In addition to altering its acidity, the presence of carbon dioxide in water also affects its electrical properties.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] When carbon dioxide dissolves in desalinated water, the electrical conductivity increases significantly from below 1 μS/cm to nearly 30 μS/cm.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] When heated, the water begins to gradually lose the conductivity induced by the presence of $\mathrm {CO_{2}}$ , especially noticeable as temperatures exceed 30 °C.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The temperature dependence of the electrical conductivity of fully deionized water without CO2 saturation is comparably low in relation to these data.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is a potent electrophile having an electrophilic reactivity that is comparable to benzaldehyde or strongly electrophilic α,β-unsaturated carbonyl compounds.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] However, unlike electrophiles of similar reactivity, the reactions of nucleophiles with CO2 are thermodynamically less favored and are often found to be highly reversible.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The reversible reaction of carbon dioxide with amines to make carbamates is used in CO2 scrubbers and has been suggested as a possible starting point for carbon capture and storage by amine gas treating.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] In metal carbon dioxide complexes, CO2 serves as a ligand, which can facilitate the conversion of CO2 to other chemicals.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The redox potential for this reaction near pH 7 is about −0.53 V *versus* the standard hydrogen electrode.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The nickel-containing enzyme carbon monoxide dehydrogenase catalyses this process.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] At low concentrations, the gas is odorless; however, at sufficiently high concentrations, it has a sharp, acidic odor.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] At standard temperature and pressure, the density of carbon dioxide is around 1.98 kg/m3, about 1.53 times that of air.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] At a pressure of 1 atm (0.101325 MPa), the gas deposits directly to a solid at temperatures below 194.6855(30) K (−78.4645(30) °C) and the solid sublimes directly to a gas above this temperature.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] In its solid state, carbon dioxide is commonly called dry ice.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Another form of solid carbon dioxide observed at high pressure is an amorphous glass-like solid.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] This form of glass, called *carbonia*, is produced by supercooling heated CO2 at extreme pressures (40–48 GPa, or about 400,000 atmospheres) in a diamond anvil.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] This discovery confirmed the theory that carbon dioxide could exist in a glass state similar to other members of its elemental family, like silicon dioxide (silica glass) and germanium dioxide.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Unlike silica and germania glasses, however, carbonia glass is not stable at normal pressures and reverts to gas when pressure is released.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] At temperatures and pressures above the critical point, carbon dioxide behaves as a supercritical fluid known as supercritical carbon dioxide.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is an end product of cellular respiration in organisms that obtain energy by breaking down sugars, fats and amino acids with oxygen as part of their metabolism.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] This includes all plants, algae and animals and aerobic fungi and bacteria.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] In vertebrates, the carbon dioxide travels in the blood from the body's tissues to the skin (e.g., amphibians) or the gills (e.g., fish), from where it dissolves in the water, or to the lungs from where it is exhaled.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] During active photosynthesis, plants can absorb more carbon dioxide from the atmosphere than they release in respiration.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Carbon fixation is a biochemical process by which atmospheric carbon dioxide is incorporated by plants, algae and cyanobacteria into energy-rich organic molecules such as glucose, thus creating their own food by photosynthesis.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Photosynthesis uses carbon dioxide and water to produce sugars from which other organic compounds can be constructed, and oxygen is produced as a by-product.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate carboxylase oxygenase, commonly abbreviated to RuBisCO, is the enzyme involved in the first major step of carbon fixation, the production of two molecules of 3-phosphoglycerate from CO2 and ribulose bisphosphate, as shown in the diagram at left.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] RuBisCO is thought to be the single most abundant protein on Earth.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Phototrophs use the products of their photosynthesis as internal food sources and as raw material for the biosynthesis of more complex organic molecules, such as polysaccharides, nucleic acids, and proteins.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] These are used for their own growth, and also as the basis of the food chains and webs that feed other organisms, including animals such as ourselves.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Some important phototrophs, the coccolithophores synthesise hard calcium carbonate scales.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] A globally significant species of coccolithophore is *Emiliania huxleyi* whose calcite scales have formed the basis of many sedimentary rocks such as limestone, where what was previously atmospheric carbon can remain fixed for geological timescales.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Plants can grow as much as 50% faster in concentrations of 1,000 ppm CO2 when compared with ambient conditions, though this assumes no change in climate and no limitation on other nutrients.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Elevated CO2 levels cause increased growth reflected in the harvestable yield of crops, with wheat, rice and soybean all showing increases in yield of 12–14% under elevated CO2 in FACE experiments.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Increased atmospheric CO2 concentrations result in fewer stomata developing on plants which leads to reduced water usage and increased water-use efficiency.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Studies using FACE have shown that CO2 enrichment leads to decreased concentrations of micronutrients in crop plants.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] This may have knock-on effects on other parts of ecosystems as herbivores will need to eat more food to gain the same amount of protein.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The concentration of secondary metabolites such as phenylpropanoids and flavonoids can also be altered in plants exposed to high concentrations of CO2.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Plants also emit CO2 during respiration, and so the majority of plants and algae, which use C3 photosynthesis, are only net absorbers during the day.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Though a growing forest will absorb many tons of CO2 each year, a mature forest will produce as much CO2 from respiration and decomposition of dead specimens (e.g., fallen branches) as is used in photosynthesis in growing plants.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Contrary to the long-standing view that they are carbon neutral, mature forests can continue to accumulate carbon and remain valuable carbon sinks, helping to maintain the carbon balance of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Additionally, and crucially to life on earth, photosynthesis by phytoplankton consumes dissolved CO2 in the upper ocean and thereby promotes the absorption of CO2 from the atmosphere.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide content in fresh air (averaged between sea-level and 10 kPa level, i.e., about 30 km (19 mi) altitude) varies between 0.036% (360 ppm) and 0.041% (412 ppm), depending on the location.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] In humans, exposure to CO2 at concentrations greater than 5% causes the development of hypercapnia and respiratory acidosis.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of 7% to 10% (70,000 to 100,000 ppm) may cause suffocation, even in the presence of sufficient oxygen, manifesting as dizziness, headache, visual and hearing dysfunction, and unconsciousness within a few minutes to an hour.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of more than 10% may cause convulsions, coma, and death.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] CO2 levels of more than 30% act rapidly leading to loss of consciousness in seconds.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Carrion feeders attracted to the carcasses are then also killed.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Children have been killed in the same way near the city of Goma by CO2 emissions from the nearby volcano Mount Nyiragongo.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The Swahili term for this phenomenon is *mazuku*.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Adaptation to increased concentrations of CO2 occurs in humans, including modified breathing and kidney bicarbonate production, in order to balance the effects of blood acidification (acidosis).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Several studies suggested that 2.0 percent inspired concentrations could be used for closed air spaces (e.g. a submarine) since the adaptation is physiological and reversible, as deterioration in performance or in normal physical activity does not happen at this level of exposure for five days.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Yet, other studies show a decrease in cognitive function even at much lower levels.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Also, with ongoing respiratory acidosis, adaptation or compensatory mechanisms will be unable to reverse the condition.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] There are few studies of the health effects of long-term continuous CO2 exposure on humans and animals at levels below 1%.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Occupational CO2 exposure limits have been set in the United States at 0.5% (5000 ppm) for an eight-hour period.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] At this CO2 concentration, International Space Station crew experienced headaches, lethargy, mental slowness, emotional irritation, and sleep disruption.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Studies in animals at 0.5% CO2 have demonstrated kidney calcification and bone loss after eight weeks of exposure.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] A study of humans exposed in 2.5 hour sessions demonstrated significant negative effects on cognitive abilities at concentrations as low as 0.1% (1000 ppm) CO2 likely due to CO2 induced increases in cerebral blood flow.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Another study observed a decline in basic activity level and information usage at 1000 ppm, when compared to 500 ppm.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] However a review of the literature found that a reliable subset of studies on the phenomenon of carbon dioxide induced cognitive impairment to only show a small effect on high-level decision making (for concentrations below 5000 ppm).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Most of the studies were confounded by inadequate study designs, environmental comfort, uncertainties in exposure doses and differing cognitive assessments used.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Similarly a study on the effects of the concentration of CO2 in motorcycle helmets has been criticized for having dubious methodology in not noting the self-reports of motorcycle riders and taking measurements using mannequins.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Further when normal motorcycle conditions were achieved (such as highway or city speeds) or the visor was raised the concentration of CO2 declined to safe levels (0.2%).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Poor ventilation is one of the main causes of excessive CO2 concentrations in closed spaces, leading to poor indoor air quality.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide differential above outdoor concentrations at steady state conditions (when the occupancy and ventilation system operation are sufficiently long that CO2 concentration has stabilized) are sometimes used to estimate ventilation rates per person.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Higher CO2 concentrations are associated with occupant health, comfort and performance degradation.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] ASHRAE Standard 62.1–2007 ventilation rates may result in indoor concentrations up to 2,100 ppm above ambient outdoor conditions.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Thus if the outdoor concentration is 400 ppm, indoor concentrations may reach 2,500 ppm with ventilation rates that meet this industry consensus standard.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations in poorly ventilated spaces can be found even higher than this (range of 3,000 or 4,000 ppm).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Miners, who are particularly vulnerable to gas exposure due to insufficient ventilation, referred to mixtures of carbon dioxide and nitrogen as "blackdamp", "choke damp" or "stythe".
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Before more effective technologies were developed, miners would frequently monitor for dangerous levels of blackdamp and other gases in mine shafts by bringing a caged canary with them as they worked.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The canary is more sensitive to asphyxiant gases than humans, and as it became unconscious would stop singing and fall off its perch.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The Davy lamp could also detect high levels of blackdamp (which sinks, and collects near the floor) by burning less brightly, while methane, another suffocating gas and explosion risk, would make the lamp burn more brightly.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] In February 2020, three people died from suffocation at a party in Moscow when dry ice (frozen CO2) was added to a swimming pool to cool it down.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] A similar accident occurred in 2018 when a woman died from CO2 fumes emanating from the large amount of dry ice she was transporting in her car.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Humans spend more and more time in a confined atmosphere (around 80-90% of the time in a building or vehicle).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] In homes, schools, nurseries and offices, there are no systematic relationships between the levels of CO2 and other pollutants, and indoor CO2 is statistically not a good predictor of pollutants linked to outdoor road (or air, etc.) traffic.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is the parameter that changes the fastest (with hygrometry and oxygen levels when humans or animals are gathered in a closed or poorly ventilated room).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] In poor countries, many open hearths are sources of CO2 and CO emitted directly into the living environment.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Local concentrations of carbon dioxide can reach high values near strong sources, especially those that are isolated by surrounding terrain.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] At the Bossoleto hot spring near Rapolano Terme in Tuscany, Italy, situated in a bowl-shaped depression about 100 m (330 ft) in diameter, concentrations of CO2 rise to above 75% overnight, sufficient to kill insects and small animals.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] After sunrise the gas is dispersed by convection.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] High concentrations of CO2 produced by disturbance of deep lake water saturated with CO2 are thought to have caused 37 fatalities at Lake Monoun, Cameroon in 1984 and 1700 casualties at Lake Nyos, Cameroon in 1986.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The body produces approximately 2.3 pounds (1.0 kg) of carbon dioxide per day per person, containing 0.63 pounds (290 g) of carbon.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] In humans, this carbon dioxide is carried through the venous system and is breathed out through the lungs, resulting in lower concentrations in the arteries.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The carbon dioxide content of the blood is often given as the partial pressure, which is the pressure which carbon dioxide would have had if it alone occupied the volume.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] In humans, the blood carbon dioxide contents are shown in the adjacent table.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is carried in blood in three different ways.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Exact percentages vary between arterial and venous blood.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Hemoglobin, the main oxygen-carrying molecule in red blood cells, carries both oxygen and carbon dioxide.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] However, the CO2 bound to hemoglobin does not bind to the same site as oxygen.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Instead, it combines with the N-terminal groups on the four globin chains.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] However, because of allosteric effects on the hemoglobin molecule, the binding of CO2 decreases the amount of oxygen that is bound for a given partial pressure of oxygen.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] This is known as the Haldane Effect, and is important in the transport of carbon dioxide from the tissues to the lungs.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Conversely, a rise in the partial pressure of CO2 or a lower pH will cause offloading of oxygen from hemoglobin, which is known as the Bohr effect.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is one of the mediators of local autoregulation of blood supply.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] If its concentration is high, the capillaries expand to allow a greater blood flow to that tissue.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Bicarbonate ions are crucial for regulating blood pH.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] A person's breathing rate influences the level of CO2 in their blood.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Breathing that is too slow or shallow causes respiratory acidosis, while breathing that is too rapid leads to hyperventilation, which can cause respiratory alkalosis.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Although the body requires oxygen for metabolism, low oxygen levels normally do not stimulate breathing.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Rather, breathing is stimulated by higher carbon dioxide levels.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] As a result, breathing low-pressure air or a gas mixture with no oxygen at all (such as pure nitrogen) can lead to loss of consciousness without ever experiencing air hunger.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] This is especially perilous for high-altitude fighter pilots.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] It is also why flight attendants instruct passengers, in case of loss of cabin pressure, to apply the oxygen mask to themselves first before helping others; otherwise, one risks losing consciousness.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The respiratory centers try to maintain an arterial CO2 pressure of 40 mmHg.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] With intentional hyperventilation, the CO2 content of arterial blood may be lowered to 10–20 mmHg (the oxygen content of the blood is little affected), and the respiratory drive is diminished.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] This is why one can hold one's breath longer after hyperventilating than without hyperventilating.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] This carries the risk that unconsciousness may result before the need to breathe becomes overwhelming, which is why hyperventilation is particularly dangerous before free diving.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] In the atmosphere of Earth, carbon dioxide (CO2) is a trace gas that plays an integral part in the greenhouse effect, carbon cycle, photosynthesis, and oceanic carbon cycle.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] It is one of three main greenhouse gases in the atmosphere of Earth.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] In 2026, the concentration of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere reached 432 ppm or 0.0432% (on a molar basis), representing a mass of 3380 gigatonnes.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] This is an increase of 54% since the start of the Industrial Revolution, up from 280 ppm during the 10,000 years prior to the mid-18th century.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The current increase in CO2 concentrations is primarily driven by the burning of fossil fuels.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Other significant human activities that emit CO2 include cement production, deforestation, and biomass burning.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The increase in atmospheric concentrations of CO2 and other long-lived greenhouse gases such as methane increase the absorption and emission of infrared radiation by the atmosphere.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] This has led to a rise in average global temperature and ocean acidification.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Another direct effect is the CO2 fertilization effect.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The increase in atmospheric concentrations of CO2 causes a range of further effects of climate change on the environment and human living conditions.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] It absorbs and emits infrared radiation at its two infrared-active vibrational frequencies.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The two wavelengths are 4.26 μm (2,347 cm−1) (antisymmetric stretching vibrational mode) and 14.99 μm (667 cm−1) (bending vibrational mode).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] CO2 plays a significant role in influencing Earth's surface temperature through the greenhouse effect.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Light emission from the Earth's surface is most intense in the infrared region between 200 and 2500 cm−1, as opposed to light emission from the much hotter Sun which is most intense in the visible region.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Absorption of infrared light at the vibrational frequencies of atmospheric CO2 traps energy near the surface, warming the surface of Earth and its lower atmosphere.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Less energy reaches the upper atmosphere, which is therefore cooler because of this absorption.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The present atmospheric concentration of CO2 is the highest for 14 million years.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of CO2 in the atmosphere were as high as 4,000 ppm during the Cambrian period about 500 million years ago, and as low as 180 ppm during the Quaternary glaciation of the last two million years.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Reconstructed temperature records for the last 420 million years indicate that atmospheric CO2 concentrations peaked at approximately 2,000 ppm.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] This peak happened during the Devonian period (400 million years ago).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Another peak occurred in the Triassic period (220–200 million years ago).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide dissolves in the ocean to form carbonic acid (H2CO3), bicarbonate (HCO3–), and carbonate (CO32–).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] There is about fifty times as much carbon dioxide dissolved in the oceans as exists in the atmosphere.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The oceans act as an enormous carbon sink, and have taken up about a third of CO2 emitted by human activity.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Ocean acidification is the ongoing decrease in the pH of the Earth's ocean.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Between 1950 and 2020, the average pH of the ocean surface fell from approximately 8.15 to 8.05.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide emissions from human activities are the primary cause of ocean acidification, with atmospheric carbon dioxide (CO2) levels exceeding 422 ppm (as of 2024).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] CO2 from the atmosphere is absorbed by the oceans.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] This chemical reaction produces carbonic acid (H2CO3) which dissociates into a bicarbonate ion (HCO−3) and a hydrogen ion (H+).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The presence of free hydrogen ions (H+) lowers the pH of the ocean, increasing acidity (this does not mean that seawater is acidic yet; it is still alkaline, with a pH higher than 8).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Marine calcifying organisms, such as mollusks and corals, are especially vulnerable because they rely on calcium carbonate to build shells and skeletons.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] A change in pH by 0.1 represents a 26% increase in hydrogen ion concentration in the world's oceans (the pH scale is logarithmic, so a change of one in pH units is equivalent to a tenfold change in hydrogen ion concentration).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Sea-surface pH and carbonate saturation states vary depending on ocean depth and location.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Colder and higher latitude waters are capable of absorbing more CO2.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] This can cause acidity to rise, lowering the pH and carbonate saturation levels in these areas.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Several other factors influence the atmosphere-ocean CO2 exchange, and thus local ocean acidification.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] These include ocean currents and upwelling zones, proximity to large continental rivers, sea ice coverage, and atmospheric exchange with nitrogen and sulfur from fossil fuel burning and agriculture.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Changes in ocean chemistry can have extensive direct and indirect effects on organisms and their habitats.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] One of the most important repercussions of increasing ocean acidity relates to the production of shells out of calcium carbonate (CaCO3).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] This process is called calcification and is important to the biology and survival of a wide range of marine organisms.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Calcification involves the precipitation of dissolved ions into solid CaCO3 structures, structures for many marine organisms, such as coccolithophores, foraminifera, crustaceans, mollusks, etc.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] After they are formed, these CaCO3 structures are vulnerable to dissolution unless the surrounding seawater contains saturating concentrations of carbonate ions (CO2−3).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Very little of the extra carbon dioxide that is added into the ocean remains as dissolved carbon dioxide.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The majority dissociates into additional bicarbonate and free hydrogen ions.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] To maintain chemical equilibrium, some of the carbonate ions already in the ocean combine with some of the hydrogen ions to make further bicarbonate.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is also introduced into the oceans through hydrothermal vents.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The *Champagne* hydrothermal vent, found at the Northwest Eifuku volcano in the Mariana Trench, produces almost pure liquid carbon dioxide, one of only two known sites in the world as of 2004, the other being in the Okinawa Trough.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carbon-dioxide] The finding of a submarine lake of liquid carbon dioxide in the Okinawa Trough was reported in 2006.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] A **carburetor** (also spelled **carburettor** or **carburetter**) is a device used by a gasoline internal combustion engine to control and mix air and fuel entering the engine.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The primary method of adding fuel to the intake air is through the Venturi effect or Bernoulli's principle or with a pitot tube in the main metering circuit, though various other components are also used to provide extra fuel or air in specific circumstances.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Since the 1990s, carburetors have been largely replaced by fuel injection for cars and trucks, but carburetors are still used by some small engines (e.g. lawnmowers, generators, and concrete mixers) and motorcycles.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] In addition, they are still widely used on piston-engine–driven aircraft.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Diesel engines have always used fuel injection instead of carburetors, as they do not compress an air-fuel mix and instead require fuel injection much later in the compression stroke.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The term "carburetor" is derived from the English verb *carburet*, meaning "to charge with hydrocarbons"; in early motoring books the product of the carburetor is *carburetted air*, i.e. air charged with hydrocarbon vapour.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] This meaning superseded that from the late eighteenth century in which *carburet* was a noun for which we now use the word *carbide*.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] A carburetor charges the intake air with vapour from a hydrocarbon-based fuel, such as petrol or autogas.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The name is spelled "carburetor" in American English and "carburettor" in British English.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Colloquial abbreviations include "carb" in the UK and North America or "carby" in Australia.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Air from the atmosphere enters the carburetor (usually via an air cleaner), has fuel added within the carburetor, then the air fuel mixture leaves the carburetor and enters the inlet manifold, then through the inlet valve(s), and finally into the combustion chamber.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Most engines use a single carburetor shared among all of the cylinders, though some high-performance engines historically had multiple carburetors and/or throats.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] If the tube is a constant diameter the configuration is slightly simpler than in the cross-section diagram shown above right.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] In most cases (except for the *accelerator pump*), the driver pressing the throttle pedal does not directly increase the fuel entering the engine.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Instead, the airflow through the carburetor increases, which in turn increases the amount of fuel drawn into the intake mixture.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] If the pressure reduction is taken as from a reduction of area along the air flow rather than from ambient pressure to the fuel entry point the effect can be described as the Venturi effect, but that is still derived from Bernoulli's principle at two positions.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] If the pressure reduction is taken as from a dynamic pressure (facing the incoming air) within the air entry point rather than from ambient pressure instead the carbureter can be described as the Pitot tube type, but that is also still derived from Bernoulli's principle at two positions.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The actual fuel and air flows are more complicated and need correction.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] This might be done variously at lower speeds or higher speeds, or over the whole range by a variable emulsion device to add air to the fuel after the main jets/s.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Zenith-Stromberg) variable jet carburetors, it was mainly controlled by varying the jet size.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The orientation of the carburetor is a key design consideration.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Older engines used **updraft** carburetors, where the air enters from below the carburetor and exits through the top.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] From the late 1930s, **downdraft** carburetors become more commonly used (especially in the United States), along with **side draft** carburetors (especially in Europe).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The main metering circuit usually consists of barrel/s which reduces to a narrow part where the air is at its highest speed, forming a choke or venturi.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Fuel is usually introduced into the air stream at that narrow part through small tubes leading from the main jet.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The change in area is only necessary for a Venturi carburetor but in other configurations the barrel/s can be of constant area with the fuel entry anywhere along it.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Downstream of a choke or venturi is a throttle (usually in the form of a butterfly valve) which is used to control the amount of air entering the carburetor.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] In a car, this throttle is usually mechanically connected to the vehicle's throttle pedal, which varies engine speed.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] At lesser throttle openings, the air speed may be insufficient to maintain the main fuel flow, so then the fuel may be supplied by the carburetor's idle and off-idle circuits usually near the narrow gap between the edge of the butterfly plate and the body to give sufficient local air speed.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] At greater throttle openings, the speed of air increases, which lowers the pressure of the air and draws more fuel into the airstream.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] At the same time, the reduced manifold vacuum results in less fuel flow through the idle and off-idle circuits.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] During cold weather fuel vaporizes less readily and tends to condense on the walls of the intake manifold, starving the cylinders of fuel and making cold starts difficult.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Additional fuel is required (for a given amount of air) to start and run the engine until it warms up, provided by a *choke valve*.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] While the engine is warming up the choke valve is partially closed, restricting the flow of air at the entrance to the carburetor.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] This increases the vacuum in the main metering circuit, causing more fuel to be supplied to the engine via the main jets.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Prior to the late 1950s the choke was manually operated by the driver, often using a lever or knob on the dashboard.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Since then, automatic chokes became more commonplace.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] These either use a bimetallic thermostat to automatically regulate the choke based on the temperature of the engine's coolant liquid, an electrical resistance heater to do so, or air drawn through a tube connected to an engine exhaust source.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] A choke left closed after the engine has warmed up increases the engine's fuel consumption and exhaust gas emissions, and causes the engine to run rough and lack power due to an over-rich fuel mixture.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] However, excessive fuel can flood an engine and prevent it from starting.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] To remove the excess fuel, many carburetors with automatic chokes allow it to be held open (by manually, depressing the accelerator pedal to the floor and briefly holding it there while cranking the starter) to allow extra air into the engine until the excess fuel is cleared out.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Another method used by carburetors to improve the operation of a cold engine is a *fast idle cam*, which is connected to the choke and prevents the throttle from closing fully while the choke is in operation.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The resulting increase in idle speed provides a more stable idle for a cold engine (by better atomizing the cold fuel) and helps the engine warm up quicker.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The system within a carburetor that meters fuel when the engine is running at low RPM.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The idle circuit is generally activated by vacuum near the (near closed) throttle plate, where the air speed increases to cause a low-pressure area in the idle passage/port, thus causing fuel to flow through the idle jet.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The idle jet is set at some constant value by the carburetor manufacturer, thus flowing a specified amount of fuel.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Many carburetors use an off-idle circuit, which includes an additional fuel jet which is briefly used as the throttle starts to open.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] This jet is located in a low-pressure area caused by the high air speed near the (partly closed) throttle.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The additional fuel it provides is used to compensate for the reduced vacuum that occurs when the throttle is opened, thus smoothing the transition from the idle circuit to the main metering circuit.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] In a four-stroke engine it is often desirable to provide extra fuel to the engine at high loads (to increase the power output and reduce engine knocking).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] A 'power valve', which is a spring-loaded valve in the carburetor that is held shut by engine vacuum, is often used to do so.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] As the airflow through the carburetor increases, the reduced manifold vacuum pulls the power valve open, allowing more fuel into the main metering circuit.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] In a two-stroke engine, the carburetor power valve operates in the opposite manner: in most circumstances the valve allows extra fuel into the engine, then at a certain engine RPM it closes to reduce the fuel entering the engine.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] This is done in order to extend the engine's maximum RPM, since many two-stroke engines can temporarily achieve higher RPM with a leaner air-fuel ratio.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] This is not to be confused with the unrelated exhaust power valve arrangements used on two-stroke engines.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] A metering rod or step-up rod system is sometimes used as an alternative to a power valve in a four-stroke engine in order to supply extra fuel at high loads.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] One end of the rods is tapered, which sits in the main metering jets and acts as a valve for fuel flow in the jets.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] At high engine loads, the rods are lifted away from the jets (either mechanically or using manifold vacuum), increasing the volume of fuel flow through the jet.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] These systems have been used by the Rochester Quadrajet and in the 1950s Carter carburetors.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] While the main metering circuit can adequately supply fuel to the engine in steady-state conditions, the inertia of fuel (being higher than that of air) causes a temporary shortfall as the throttle is opened.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Therefore, an accelerator pump is often used to briefly provide extra fuel as the throttle is opened.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] When the driver presses the throttle pedal, a small piston or diaphragm pump injects extra fuel directly into the carburetor throat.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The accelerator pump can also be used to "prime" an engine with extra fuel prior to attempting a cold start.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] In order to ensure an adequate supply at all times, carburetors include a reservoir of fuel, called a "float chamber" or "float bowl".
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Fuel is delivered to the float chamber by a fuel pump or by gravity with the fuel tank located higher than the carburetor.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] A floating inlet valve regulates the fuel entering the float chamber, assuring a constant level.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] In some small engines that may instead of a float chamber just use a fuel tank close below the carburetor and use the fuel suction to supply the fuel.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Unlike in a fuel injected engine, the fuel system in a carbureted engine is not pressurized.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] For engines where the intake air travelling through the carburetor is pressurized (such as where the carburetor is downstream of a supercharger) the entire carburetor must be contained in an airtight pressurized box to operate.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] However, this is not necessary where the carburetor is upstream of the supercharger.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Problems of fuel boiling and vapor lock can occur in carbureted engines, especially in hotter climates.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Since the float chamber is located close to the engine, heat from the engine (including for several hours after the engine is shut off) can cause the fuel to heat up to the point of vaporization.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] This causes air bubbles in the fuel (similar to the air bubbles that necessitate brake bleeding), which prevents the flow of fuel and is known as 'vapor lock'.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] If an engine must be operated when the carburetor is not in an upright orientation (for example in a chainsaw or airplane), a float chamber and gravity activated float valve would not be suitable.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Instead, a diaphragm chamber is typically used.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] This consists of a flexible diaphragm on one side of the fuel chamber, connected to a needle valve which regulates the fuel entering the chamber.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] As the flowrate of the air in the chamber (controlled by the throttling valve/butterfly valve) decreases, the diaphragm moves inward (downward), which closes the needle valve to admit less fuel.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] As the flowrate of the air in the chamber increases, the diaphragm moves outward (upward) which opens the needle valve to admit more fuel, allowing the engine to generate more power.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] A balanced state is reached which creates a steady fuel reservoir level, that remains constant in any orientation.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The basic design for a carburetor consists of a single venturi (main metering circuit), though designs with two or four venturi (two-barrel and four-barrel carburetors respectively) are also quite commonplace.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Typically the barrels consist of "primary" barrel(s) used for lower load situations and secondary barrel(s) activating when required to provide additional air/fuel at higher loads.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The primary and secondary venturi are often sized differently and incorporate different features to suit the situations in which they are used.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Many four-barrel carburetors use two primary and two secondary barrels.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] A four-barrel design of two primary and two secondary barrels was commonly used in V8 engines to conserve fuel at low engine speeds while still affording an adequate supply at high.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The use of multiple carburetors (e.g., a carburetor for each cylinder or pair of cylinders) also results in the intake air being drawn through multiple venturi.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Some high-performance engines have used multiple two-barrel or four-barrel carburetors, for example six two-barrel carburetors on Ferrari V12s.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] In 1826, American engineer Samuel Morey received a patent for a "gas or vapor engine", which had a carburetor that mixed turpentine and air.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] In 1888/1889 German engineer Siegfried Marcus produced a car powered by a petrol engine (which also debuted the first magneto ignition system).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Karl Benz introduced his single-cylinder four-stroke powered Benz Patent-Motorwagen in 1885.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] All three of these engines used surface carburetors, which operated by moving air across the top of a vessel containing the fuel.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The first float-fed carburetor design, which used an atomizer nozzle, was introduced by German engineers Wilhelm Maybach and Gottlieb Daimler in their 1885 *Grandfather Clock engine*.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The Butler Petrol Cycle car—built in England in 1888—also used a float-fed carburetor.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] In 1892 Maybach produced an important carburetor with a jet spraying into a venturi, as would become the norm; this was patented in 1893.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The first carburetor for a stationary engine was patented in 1893 by Hungarian engineers János Csonka and Donát Bánki.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The first four-barrel carburetors were the Carter Carburetor WCFB and the identical Rochester 4GC, introduced in various General Motors models for 1952.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Oldsmobile referred the new carburetor as the "Quadri-Jet" (original spelling) while Buick called it the "Airpower".
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] In the United States, carburetors were the common method of fuel delivery for most US-made gasoline (petrol) engines until the late 1980s, when fuel injection became the preferred method.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] One of the last motorsport users of carburetors was NASCAR, which switched to electronic fuel injection after the 2011 Sprint Cup series.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] NASCAR still uses the four-barrel carburetor in the NASCAR Xfinity Series.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] In Europe, carburetors were largely replaced by fuel injection in the late 1980s, although fuel injection had been increasingly used in luxury cars and sports cars since the 1970s.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] EEC legislation required all vehicles sold and produced in member countries to have a catalytic converter after December 1992.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] This legislation had been in the pipeline for some time, with many cars becoming available with catalytic converters or fuel injection from around 1990.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] A significant concern for aircraft engines is the formation of ice inside the carburetor.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The temperature of air within the carburetor can be reduced by up to 40 °C (72 °F), due to a combination of the reduced air pressure in the venturi and the latent heat of the evaporating fuel.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The conditions during the descent to landing are particularly conducive to icing, since the engine is run at idle for a prolonged period with the throttle closed.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Icing can also occur in cruise conditions at altitude.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] A carburetor heat system is often used to prevent icing.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] This system consists of a secondary air intake which passes around the exhaust, in order to heat the air before it enters the carburetor.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Typically, the system is operated by the pilot manually switching the intake air to travel via the heated intake path as required.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] The carburetor heat system reduces the power output (due to the lower density of heated air) and causes the intake air filter to be bypassed, therefore the system is only used when there is a risk of icing.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] If the engine is operating at idle RPM, another method to prevent icing is to periodically open the throttle, which increases the air temperature within the carburetor.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Carburetor icing also occurs on other applications and various methods have been employed to solve this problem.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] On inline engines the intake and exhaust manifolds are on the same side of the head.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Heat from the exhaust is used to warm the intake manifold and in turn the carburetor.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] On V configurations, exhaust gases were directed from one head through the intake cross over to the other head.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] One method for regulating the exhaust flow on the cross over for intake warming was a weighted eccentric butterfly valve called a heat riser that remained closed at idle and opened at higher exhaust flow.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] Some vehicles used a heat stove around the exhaust manifold.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] It was connected to the air filter intake via tubing and supplied warmed air to the air filter.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/carburetor] A vacuum controlled butterfly valve pre heat tube on the intake horn of the air cleaner would open allowing cooler air when engine load increased.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] In electromagnetism, **charge density** is the amount of electric charge per unit length, surface area, or volume.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] **Volume charge density** (symbolized by the Greek letter ρ) is the quantity of charge per unit volume, measured in the SI system in coulombs per cubic meter (C⋅m−3), at any point in a volume.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] **Surface charge density** (σ) is the quantity of charge per unit area, measured in coulombs per square meter (C⋅m−2), at any point on a surface charge distribution on a two dimensional surface.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] **Linear charge density** (λ) is the quantity of charge per unit length, measured in coulombs per meter (C⋅m−1), at any point on a line charge distribution.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] Charge density can be either positive or negative, since electric charge can be either positive or negative.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] Like mass density, charge density can vary with position.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] Due to the conservation of electric charge, the charge density in any volume can only change if an electric current of charge flows into or out of the volume.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] This is expressed by a continuity equation which links the rate of change of charge density $\rho ({\boldsymbol {x}})$ and the current density ${\boldsymbol {J}}({\boldsymbol {x}})$ .
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] Since all charge is carried by subatomic particles, which can be idealized as points, the concept of a *continuous* charge distribution is an approximation, which becomes inaccurate at small length scales.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] A charge distribution is ultimately composed of individual charged particles separated by regions containing no charge.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] For example, the charge in an electrically charged metal object is made up of conduction electrons moving randomly in the metal's crystal lattice.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] Static electricity is caused by surface charges consisting of electrons and ions near the surface of objects, and the space charge in a vacuum tube is composed of a cloud of free electrons moving randomly in space.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] The charge carrier density in a conductor is equal to the number of mobile charge carriers (electrons, ions, etc.) per unit volume.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] The charge density at any point is equal to the charge carrier density multiplied by the elementary charge on the particles.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] This is the meaning of 'charge distribution' and 'charge density' used in chemistry and chemical bonding.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] An electron is represented by a *wavefunction* $\psi ({\boldsymbol {x}})$ whose square is proportional to the probability of finding the electron at any point ${\boldsymbol {x}}$ in space, so $|\psi ({\boldsymbol {x}})|^{2}$ is proportional to the charge density of the electron at any point.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] In atoms and molecules the charge of the electrons is distributed in clouds called orbitals which surround the atom or molecule, and are responsible for chemical bonds.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] Following are the definitions for continuous charge distributions.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] Within the context of electromagnetism, the subscripts are usually dropped for simplicity: *λ*, *σ*, *ρ*.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] Other notations may include: *ρℓ*, *ρs*, *ρv*, *ρL*, *ρS*, *ρV* etc.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] In dielectric materials, the total charge of an object can be separated into "free" and "bound" charges.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] In terms of volume charge densities, the **total** charge density is: $\rho =\rho _{\text{f}}+\rho _{\text{b}}\,.$ as for surface charge densities: $\sigma =\sigma _{\text{f}}+\sigma _{\text{b}}\,.$ where subscripts "f" and "b" denote "free" and "bound" respectively.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] The negative sign arises due to the opposite signs on the charges in the dipoles, one end is within the volume of the object, the other at the surface.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] A more rigorous derivation is given below.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] See Maxwell's equations and constitutive relation for more details.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] The equivalent proofs for linear charge density and surface charge density follow the same arguments as above.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] For a single point charge *q* at position **r**0 inside a region of 3d space *R*, like an electron, the volume charge density can be expressed by the Dirac delta function: $\rho _{q}(\mathbf {r} )=q\delta (\mathbf {r} -\mathbf {r} _{0})$ where **r** is the position to calculate the charge.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] As always, the integral of the charge density over a region of space is the charge contained in that region.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] This can be extended to *N* discrete point-like charge carriers.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] Similar equations are used for the linear and surface charge densities.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] In special relativity, the length of a segment of wire depends on velocity of observer because of length contraction, so charge density will also depend on velocity.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] Anthony French has described how the magnetic field force of a current-bearing wire arises from this relative charge density.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] He used (p 260) a Minkowski diagram to show "how a neutral current-bearing wire appears to carry a net charge density as observed in a moving frame." When a charge density is measured in a moving frame of reference it is called **proper charge density**.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] It turns out the charge density *ρ* and current density **J** transform together as a four-current vector under Lorentz transformations.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] When the wavefunction is normalized - the average charge in the region **r** ∈ *R* is $Q=\int _{R}q|\psi (\mathbf {r} )|^{2}\,d^{3}\mathbf {r}$ where *d*3**r** is the integration measure over 3d position space.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] Where *I* is the kinetic and potential energy of electrons due to positive charges, *J* is the electron electron interaction energy and *K* is the exchange energy of electrons.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] The charge density appears in the continuity equation for electric current, and also in Maxwell's Equations.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] It is the principal source term of the electromagnetic field; when the charge distribution moves, this corresponds to a current density.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] The charge density of molecules impacts chemical and separation processes.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] For example, charge density influences metal-metal bonding and hydrogen bonding.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/charge-density] For separation processes such as nanofiltration, the charge density of ions influences their rejection by the membrane.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] In internal combustion engines, **exhaust gas recirculation** (**EGR**) is a nitrogen oxide (NO*x*) emissions reduction technique used in petrol/gasoline, diesel engines and some hydrogen engines.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] EGR works by recirculating a portion of an engine's exhaust gas back to the engine cylinders.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] The exhaust gas displaces atmospheric air and reduces O2 in the combustion chamber.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Reducing the amount of oxygen reduces the amount of fuel that can burn in the cylinder thereby reducing peak in-cylinder temperatures.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] The actual amount of recirculated exhaust gas varies with the engine operating parameters.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] In the combustion cylinder, NO*x* is produced by high-temperature mixtures of atmospheric nitrogen and oxygen, and this usually occurs at cylinder peak pressure.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] In a spark-ignition engine, an ancillary benefit of recirculating exhaust gases via an external EGR valve is an increase in efficiency, as charge dilution allows a larger throttle position and reduces associated pumping losses.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Mazda's turbocharged SkyActiv gasoline direct injection engine uses recirculated and cooled exhaust gases to reduce combustion chamber temperatures, thereby permitting the engine to run at higher boost levels before the air-fuel mixture must be enriched to prevent engine knocking.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] In a gasoline engine, this inert exhaust displaces some amount of combustible charge in the cylinder, effectively reducing the quantity of charge available for combustion without affecting the air–fuel ratio.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] In a diesel engine, the exhaust gas replaces some of the excess oxygen in the pre-combustion mixture.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Because NO*x* forms primarily when a mixture of nitrogen and oxygen is subjected to high temperature, the lower combustion chamber temperatures caused by EGR reduces the amount of NO*x* that the combustion process generates.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Gases re-introduced from EGR systems will also contain near equilibrium concentrations of NO*x* and CO; the small fraction initially within the combustion chamber inhibits the total net production of these and other pollutants when sampled on a time average.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Chemical properties of different fuels limit how much EGR may be used.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] For example methanol is more tolerant to EGR than gasoline.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] The first EGR systems were crude; some were as simple as an orifice jet between the exhaust and intake tracts which admitted exhaust to the intake tract whenever the engine was running.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Difficult starting, rough idling, reduced performance and lost fuel economy inevitably resulted.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] By 1973, an EGR valve controlled by manifold vacuum opened or closed to admit exhaust to the intake tract only under certain conditions.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Control systems grew more sophisticated as automakers gained experience; Volkswagen's "Coolant Controlled Exhaust Gas Recirculation" system of 1973 exemplified this evolution: a coolant temperature sensor blocked vacuum to the EGR valve until the engine reached normal operating temperature.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] This prevented driveability problems due to unnecessary exhaust induction; NO*x* forms under elevated temperature conditions generally not present with a cold engine.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Moreover, the EGR valve was controlled, in part, by vacuum drawn from the carburetor's venturi, which allowed more precise constraint of EGR flow to only those engine load conditions under which NO*x* is likely to form.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Later, backpressure transducers were added to the EGR valve control to further tailor EGR flow to engine load conditions.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Most modern engines now need exhaust gas recirculation to meet NO*x* emissions standards.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] However, recent innovations have led to the development of engines that do not require them.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] The 3.6 Chrysler Pentastar engine is one example that does not require EGR.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] The exhaust gas contains water vapor and carbon dioxide which both have lower heat capacity ratio than air.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Adding exhaust gas therefore reduces pressure and temperature during the isentropic compression in the cylinder, thereby lowering the adiabatic flame temperature.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] In a typical automotive spark-ignited (SI) engine, 5% to 15% of the exhaust gas is routed back to the intake as EGR.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] The maximum quantity is limited by the need of the mixture to sustain a continuous flame front during the combustion event; excessive EGR in poorly set up applications can cause misfires and partial burns.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Although EGR does measurably slow combustion, this can largely be compensated for by advancing spark timing.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] The impact of EGR on engine efficiency largely depends on the specific engine design, and sometimes leads to a compromise between efficiency and NO*x* emissions.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] EGR is typically not employed at high loads because it would reduce peak power output.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] This is because it reduces the intake charge density.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] EGR is also omitted at idle (low-speed, zero load) because it would cause unstable combustion, resulting in rough idle.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Since the EGR system recirculates a portion of exhaust gases, over time the valve can become clogged with carbon deposits, which will prevent it from operating properly.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Clogged EGR valves can sometimes be cleaned, but replacement is necessary if the valve is faulty.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Because diesel engines depend on the heat of compression to ignite their fuel, they are fundamentally different from spark-ignited engines.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] The physical process of diesel fuel combustion is such that the most complete combustion occurs at the highest temperatures.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] However, the production of nitrogen oxides (NO*x*) increases at high temperatures.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] The goal of EGR is thus to reduce NO*x* production by reducing the combustion temperature.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] In modern diesel engines, the EGR gas is usually cooled with a heat exchanger to allow the introduction of a greater mass of recirculated gas.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] However, uncooled EGR designs do exist; these are often referred to as hot-gas recirculation (HGR).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Cooled EGR components are exposed to repeated, rapid changes in temperatures, which can cause coolant leak and catastrophic engine failure.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Unlike spark-ignition engines, diesel engines are not limited by the need for a contiguous flamefront.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Furthermore, since diesels always operate with excess air, they benefit (in terms of reduced NO*x* output) from EGR rates as high as 50%.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] However, a 50% EGR rate is only suitable when the diesel engine is at idle, since this is when there is otherwise a large excess of air.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Because modern diesel engines often have a throttle, EGR can reduce the need for throttling, thereby eliminating this type of loss in the same way that it does for spark-ignited engines.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] In a naturally aspirated (i.e. non-turbocharged) engine, such a reduction in throttling also reduces the problem of engine oil being sucked past the piston rings into the cylinder and causing oil-derived carbon deposits there.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] In diesel engines in particular, EGR systems come with serious drawbacks, one of which is a reduction in engine longevity.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] For example, because the EGR system routes exhaust gas directly back into the cylinder intake without any form of filtration, this exhaust gas contains carbon particulates.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Because these tiny particles are abrasive, the recirculation of this material back into the cylinder increases engine wear.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] This is because these carbon particles will blow by the piston rings (causing piston-cylinder-interface wear in the process) and then end up in the crankcase oil, where they will cause further wear throughout the engine simply because their tiny size passes through typical oil filters.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] This enables them to be recirculated indefinitely (until the next oil change takes place).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Exhaust gas—which consists largely of nitrogen, carbon dioxide, and water vapor—has a higher specific heat than air, so it still serves to lower peak combustion temperatures.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] However, adding EGR to a diesel engine reduces the specific heat ratio of the combustion gases in the power stroke.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] This reduces the amount of power that can be extracted by the piston, thereby reducing the thermodynamic efficiency.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] EGR also tends to reduce the completeness of fuel combustion during the power stroke.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] This is evident by the increase in particulate emissions that correspond to an increase in EGR.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Particulate matter (mainly carbon and also known as soot) that is not burned in the power stroke represents wasted energy.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Because of stricter regulations on particulate matter (PM), the soot-increasing effect of EGR required the introduction of further emission controls in order to compensate for the resulting PM emission increases.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] The most common soot-control device is a diesel particulate filter (DPF) installed downstream of the engine in the exhaust system.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] This captures soot but causes a reduction in fuel efficiency due to the back pressure created.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Diesel particulate filters come with their own set of very specific operational and maintenance requirements.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Firstly, as the DPF captures the soot particles (which are made far more numerous due to the use of EGR), the DPF itself progressively becomes loaded with soot.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] This soot must then be burned off, either actively or passively.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] At sufficiently high temperatures, the nitrogen dioxide component of NO*x* emissions is the primary oxidizer of the soot caught in the DPF at normal operating temperatures.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] This process is known as passive regeneration, and it is only partially effective at burning off the captured soot.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] At high EGR rates, the effectiveness of passive regeneration is further reduced.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] This, in turn, necessitates periodic active regeneration of the DPF by burning diesel fuel directly in the oxidation catalyst in order to significantly increase exhaust-gas temperatures through the DPF to the point where PM is incinerated by the residual oxygen in the exhaust.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Because diesel fuel and engine oil both contain non-burnable (i.e. metallic and mineral) impurities, the incineration of soot (PM) in the DPF leaves behind a residue known as ash.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] For this reason, after repeated regeneration events, eventually the DPF must either be physically removed and cleaned in a special external process, or it must be replaced.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] As noted earlier, the feeding of the low-oxygen exhaust gas into the diesel engine's air intake engenders lower combustion temperatures, thereby reducing emissions of NO*x*.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] By replacing some of the fresh air intake with inert gases EGR also allows the engine to reduce the amount of injected fuel without compromising ideal air-fuel mixture ratio, therefore reducing fuel consumption in low engine load situation (for ex. while the vehicle is coasting or cruising).
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Power is not reduced by EGR at any times, as EGR is not employed in high load engine situations.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] This allows engines to still deliver maximum power when needed, but lower fuel consumption despite large cylinder volume when partial load is sufficient to meet the power needs of the car and the driver.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] EGR has nothing to do with oil vapor re-routing from a positive crankcase ventilation system (PCV) system, as the latter is only there to reduce oil vapor emissions, and can be present on engines with or without any EGR system.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] However, the tripartite mixture resulting from employing both EGR and PCV in an engine (i.e. exhaust gas, fresh air, and oil vapour) can cause the buildup of sticky tar in the intake manifold and valves.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] This mixture can also cause problems with components such as swirl flaps, where fitted.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] These problems, which effectively take the form of an undesirable positive-feedback loop, will worsen as the engine ages.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] For example, as the piston rings progressively wear out, more crankcase oil will get into the exhaust stream.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Simultaneously, more fuel and soot and combustion byproducts will gain access to the engine oil.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Modern cooled EGR systems help reduce engine wear by using the waste heat recouped from the recirculated gases to help warm the coolant and hence the engine block faster to operating temperature.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Lowering combustion temperatures also helps reducing the oxidization of engine oil, as the most significant factor affecting that is exposure of the oil to high temperatures.
[src:exhaust-gas-recirculation/exhaust-gas-recirculation] Although engine manufacturers have refused to release details of the effect of EGR on fuel economy, the EPA regulations of 2002 that led to the introduction of cooled EGR were associated with a 3% drop in engine efficiency, thus bucking the trend of a 0.5% annual increase.
